Letâ€™s clearly break down Spring vs Spring Boot â€” their purpose, differences, and when to use which.

ğŸŒ± What is Spring?
Spring Framework is a comprehensive Java framework that provides infrastructure support for developing enterprise-level applications.
It gives you the core building blocks, but you need to configure everything manually.

âœ… Key Features of Spring
Dependency Injection (IoC): Manages object creation and dependencies.

Aspect-Oriented Programming (AOP): Helps with cross-cutting concerns like logging, transactions, etc.

Spring MVC: Framework for building web applications.

Spring JDBC / ORM: Simplifies database operations.

Security, Transactions, Caching, etc.

âš ï¸ Drawbacks
Requires a lot of configuration (XML or Java-based).

You must set up server, dependencies, and project structure manually.

ğŸš€ What is Spring Boot?
Spring Boot is built on top of the Spring Framework.
It simplifies the development process by automating configuration and providing ready-to-use defaults.

Think of Spring Boot as Spring + Auto Configuration + Embedded Server + Starter Dependencies

âœ… Key Features of Spring Boot
Auto Configuration: Automatically configures beans based on classpath and project setup.

Starter Dependencies: One-line dependency management (e.g., spring-boot-starter-web).

Embedded Servers: Comes with Tomcat, Jetty, or Undertow built-in.

Production-ready: Includes metrics, health checks, and monitoring with Actuator.

Spring Boot CLI: Allows running apps with minimal code.

âš™ï¸ Example
Spring Boot:

@SpringBootApplication
public class DemoApplication {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        SpringApplication.run(DemoApplication.class, args);
    }
}
No XML. No external server setup. Just run the app.

ğŸ” Comparison Table
Feature	Spring Framework	Spring Boot
Setup	Manual, requires XML/Java config	Auto-configured
Dependency Management	Manual (add each dependency)	Simplified (starters)
Server Setup	External (Tomcat/Jetty)	Embedded servers
Configuration	Verbose, complex	Minimal, automatic
Deployment	WAR file	JAR file (self-contained)
Focus	Framework for enterprise apps	Rapid development platform
Learning Curve	Steeper	Easier for beginners
ğŸ§­ When to Use What
Situation	Recommended
You want fine-grained control over configuration	Spring Framework
You need to quickly develop and deploy applications	Spring Boot
You are building microservices	Spring Boot
Youâ€™re maintaining an old enterprise system	Likely Spring Framework
ğŸ§© Example Analogy
Spring is like buying separate car parts and assembling the car yourself.
Spring Boot is like getting a pre-assembled car that you can start and drive immediately.

